@p-vital I don't think you understand the thrust of this change: the machinery for storing flask-login data would be abstracted and by default would be placed into its own cookie. Applications would be free to use this abstraction to put the data wherever else they might like.

This change is important because it ensures that flask-login does not mangle application-level data. E.g. data stored in the session. It also makes it easier for flask-login to purge its own data without accidentally leaving behind stale bits.

I can think of no reason why providing an abstraction which would allow anyone to do whatever they please is not quantifiably better than what we have today--at the same time it fixes the previous issues we've run into.

