@mjmg if you do not want to use full mkl (core), please try the following.

export MKLROOT=/usr/local (change to location where you have MKL2017/MKLML , not full MKL)

the above export will bypass downloading MKLML/MKL2017, and will just use your location.

please build with,
make -j $(nproc) USE_OPENCV=1 USE_MKL2017=1 USE_MKL2017_EXPERIMENTAL=1 USE_BLAS=

The above will build with BLAS set to MKLML and LAPACK enabled by default. The empty USE_BLAS will force the build to use MKLML's blas.

@jeffreypicard 
So, it looks like the execution_date resolves down to "second" granularity. For async workloads, we will need a way to avoid collisions for the same second. Is it possible to specify these dates down to milliseconds or microseconds instead? I don't know personally.. and if we have some string parsing that locks in the format to seconds, that's may be a problem in the UI and other parts of the code.  

A nonce won't help because many tables will have collisions on the same execution date - we need to avoid collisions on the execution date. In the scheduled use-cases, this can be avoided. In the async-driven use-cases, we need  to add logic to avoid the collision.

