@WeatherGod By the way, I'm sorry I didn't address your other question yesterday. Regarding specifying the format, I'd say that I have some ideas for moving in this direction, but in some ways, I'm not entirely sure that `dateutil.parser.parser` is the right thing to make particularly strict like that. I think that is in contrast to its "auto-magical" properties, and honestly for the most part if you know the format of the string, you should probably be using `datetime.strptime`. The main problem is that format strings are a fairly limited DSL and don't allow any sort of conditional evaluation, but as you go down the road of making more and more configurations, you end up with a fairly complicated language that has grown organically - a very dangerous situation from a design perspective.

In my head I'm playing around with the idea of a parser that first breaks the string down into an intermediate representation from which a date could be parsed, and then uses that to parse the date. I think adding in this "intermediate representation" seam could then be useful for specifying various aspects of how you want your date parsed.

That said, I don't know how feasible that would be. There's a lot of weird stuff about the context of the string that may make it very difficult to represent in the abstract in a way that can be easily exposed downstream.

